There are many specific safety features in place at the facility.  Some of the features in place at the Lexington GE Lighting facility to prevent a chemical accident include:

? Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;
? Secondary containment dike at the tank truck off-loading area to contain the full content of the tank truck;
? Secondary containment dikes around the chemical storage tanks to contain a spill;
? Full enclosure of the storage tanks in a separate on-site building;
? Operation of four fume scrubbers which serve vents located within the chemical storage and working areas;  
? Extensive safety information about the processes available to employees;
? Written operating procedures that identify plant policies on emergency response actions;
? Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work-practices;
? Scheduled maintenance programs to ensure equipment reliability - includes equipment testing and inspection;
? Compliance auditing to ensure standards are being followed;
? A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards; and
? Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes. 

FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

The Kentucky Glass Plant has an outstanding record of accident prevention, which demonstrates its commitment to public and worker safety.  Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how to prevent future occurrences.  

The RMP requires that all incidents involving regulated chemicals that resulted in any off-site impact or significant on-site impact be reported in this document.  GE Lighting has had two releases of HF acid within this 5-year history that resulted in on-site or off-site impacts as defined by EPA.  These incidents occurred in 1999.

